View this post on the web at https://post.substack.com/p/the-highway-kind

Editor=E2=80=99s note: We=E2=80=99ve invited a group of writers to profile =
their favorite Substackers. This is the first in that series.
America, they say, is already dead and doesn=E2=80=99t know it. Whatever my=
stery or magic once haunted its blue highways and back roads has long since=
 fled, and anyone lighting out for the territories in search of meaning and=
 adventure will find only a grim, desiccated interior; a zombieland held to=
gether by cheap entertainment, political rancor, poisonous food, and despai=
r.
Writers, too, have failed at their task. The complaint goes something like =
this: No longer channeling the spirit of the muddy river country that anima=
ted Twain, Melville, and Hemingway, our literati confine themselves to writ=
ing insular dispatches from cosmopolitan enclaves, in which a familiar set =
of themes=E2=80=94bad dates, grad school, Manhattan bohemia, going on your =
phone=E2=80=94are played in slightly different ways. It all has a feeling o=
f enervating decadence: trifles, amusements, cultural exhaustion. Any vital=
 voice in American letters, should it ever appear, wouldn=E2=80=99t find an=
y purchase. And anyway, no one even reads.
Those are common views, and they=E2=80=99re not entirely baseless. It=E2=80=
=99s hard not to feel pessimistic if you look too long at the hollowed-out =
interior of the country and at the obscene divide between wealthy and wretc=
hed in the metropoles. And it=E2=80=99s hard to feel good about the state o=
f the written word if you don=E2=80=99t venture beyond the New York Times b=
estseller list. But I know better. I haven=E2=80=99t yet written it all off=
 as unsalvageable. I have hope for both the country and its literary output=
, in no small part because I read Meaghan Garvey .
Purely on the strength of her Substack newsletter, SCARY COOL SAD GOODBYE ,=
 Garvey has become one of my favorite working writers. The =E2=80=9Cvibes-b=
ased newsletter=E2=80=9D constructs an invisible world, a shadow America th=
at can be glimpsed out on the side streets and at the edges of the radio di=
al. Garvey writes lucid and precise essays on figures like Lucia Berlin, Ha=
rmony Korine, David Lynch, and Elvis and interviews characters who seem plu=
cked from tall tales, like Raven Myers, the =E2=80=9Ctrucker/photographer q=
ueen of the Southwest,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CTitus Pullo,=E2=80=9D the worl=
d=E2=80=99s leading expert on Chicagoland-area barbecue joints.
But the heart of the newsletter lies in dispatches from her adventures arou=
nd the interior of the country. In her battleship of a =E2=80=9993 DeVille,=
 =E2=80=9Cblood-red on the outside, the dashboard, the leather seats,=E2=80=
=9D she travels to various dive bars, supper clubs, honky-tonks, ghost town=
s, and nudist camps, and chronicles the environs and inhabitants in a charm=
ing and captivating voice: the voice of a friend. You could call it travel =
writing or journalism, but it=E2=80=99s something more than that. It feels =
like an attempt to map a vision of this country and its culture that acts a=
s a small counter to the forces that conspire to cheapen and degrade everyd=
ay life. As Biz Sherbert [ https://substack.com/redirect/27e830b9-56d1-4864=
-8548-25245a2b7dac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9e=
cHmePkbA3ys ] once said about a Lana Del Rey concert, everyone=E2=80=99s lo=
oking for their own, better version of America.
Garvey began SCARY COOL SAD GOODBYE in 2020, after a long, grinding stint a=
s a music and culture journalist in the heady days of Vice and Pitchfork. I=
ts philosophy, she tells me over the phone, is to use her =E2=80=9Cintuitio=
n and good cheer=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cfling [herself] out into the Midwest =
and find the story, or the conversation, or the very interesting person, or=
 the portal to another realm that happens to be in a dive bar.=E2=80=9D Tha=
t keen intuition has brought her to places like the Pinehurst Inn [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/2f5e0194-2651-42c3-9cf0-e6e6643a6283?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5=
qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ], a surreal spot in =
=E2=80=9CNorthern Michigan=E2=80=99s Lynchian underbelly=E2=80=9D where the=
 barflies brag that they=E2=80=99ve been to jail in 30 states and an Elvis =
impersonator called =E2=80=9CAlvis=E2=80=9D wails out the songs of the King=
 in his sweat-soaked Vegas era, and to House on the Rock [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/734dc512-5cc8-4fcb-8e1=
0-3b6f5ed3ec2f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.=
AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ], an utterly bizarre wonderlan=
d of themed rooms deep in the Wisconsin woods, which Garvey describes as a =
=E2=80=9Ctweaked-out Graceland.=E2=80=9D (Elvis, you may have noticed, inad=
vertently cameos in many of these posts. I tend to think of him as the guar=
dian angel or spirit animal of SCARY COOL SAD GOODBYE, perhaps of America i=
tself.)
By no means, however, is the purpose of the newsletter just to gawp at the =
strange goings-on in the heartland. Garvey has a real regard for these plac=
es and the people who inhabit them, and for a time when weirdos had more le=
eway to create their own odd, personal worlds. =E2=80=9CI yearn for a more =
individualized time,=E2=80=9D she tells me. =E2=80=9CNot just with people b=
ut with places, where you could go to a city and not spin in a circle and b=
e like, I could be in Nashville, Cleveland, San Francisco, I could be anywh=
ere, and I wouldn=E2=80=99t know, because it=E2=80=99s all the same.=E2=80=
=9D In my favorite of her essays [ https://substack.com/redirect/b8c5274e-9=
7fb-4a3e-b664-b7d11e214bb7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdY=
u_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ], a long, sad, beautiful ramble around Texas in the fo=
otsteps of the great country singer Townes Van Zandt, she draws a pointed c=
ontrast between what remains of the Austin of the outlaw country era and th=
e present-day =E2=80=9Ctwisted yuppie shithole=E2=80=9D that uses the great=
 names of its past to furnish expensive cocktails and luxury high-rises. Wh=
ile chasing Townes=E2=80=99s ghost around this land of motels =E2=80=9C=E2=
=80=98groovy=E2=80=99 in that Austin way, retro but millennial in schemes o=
f pink and orange=E2=80=9D and dismal bars where =E2=80=9Cindustrial chic m=
eets urban cowboy,=E2=80=9D she also runs into the wreckage of her own love=
 life. Reading an essay about a country singer that suddenly swerves into e=
x-boyfriend talk is usually a signal to abort mission, but Garvey=E2=80=99s=
 tone is perfect: wry, self-deprecating, and sweetly melancholic, in the tr=
adition of her avowed model Eve Babitz.
I checked out of the motel and fired up the LoveMobile, checking the flyer =
for the church party, which began in 20 minutes. Inside the glove compartme=
nt my old cassettes remained, but for now I drove in silence. The morning=
=E2=80=99s incident had thrown me. In the dream Charlie recounted, I had be=
en seduced by Townes, who=E2=80=99d then delivered him a song, completed bu=
t for the transcription. Townes himself insisted certain songs arrived in d=
reams, though not everything he said was exactly to be believed. Still, str=
anger things have happened. In any case, there went my love life, messing u=
p my work again. Why=E2=80=99d Charlie have to go and make my Townes thing =
about him? Sobriety was my guess. Being freshly out of detox, as he=E2=80=
=99d been since New Year=E2=80=99s Day, can make a person grandiose.
Despite her penchant for midcentury nostalgia, Garvey avoids treating the p=
laces and people she writes about as fading relics of a brighter past. Her =
personal mythology includes Elvis and Marilyn but also Lana Del Rey and Van=
derpump Rules; when she gives a list of summer reading recommendations [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/e3b3acba-a43a-4bef-ade6-1f4463853508?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ], it includes Em=
ma Cline and Pamela Anderson=E2=80=99s autobiography as well as F. Scott Fi=
tzgerald and Charles Portis. The bars and tourist traps she visits might be=
 pleasingly retro, but they=E2=80=99re still living parts of the landscape,=
 with regulars and new customers and stories yet untold. More than most wri=
ters, she makes me feel as if what is most important to me in art and life =
has not been discarded by time, that I am continuing to participate in an a=
ctive cultural tradition that corporations and algorithms, despite their be=
st efforts, have not been able to entirely crush. =E2=80=9CI like a place t=
hat=E2=80=99s been around for a hundred years,=E2=80=9D she says, =E2=80=9C=
because it flies in the face of doomers.=E2=80=9D
Now, because I happen to love diners, road trips, dive bars, and torch song=
s, it=E2=80=99s quite natural for me to feel aesthetically aligned with Gar=
vey. But my feelings toward her work go beyond shared sensibilities. I put =
her in a special category of writers who charge me up, who I reach for when=
 I need to roll down life=E2=80=99s window and hit myself with a blast of b=
racing air. She reminds me not to get stuck in dull routine, that I control=
 my own destiny, and can, if I so choose, hop in my car, hit the road, and =
spend a few days talking to strangers. She has crafted herself into the mai=
n character of her own ongoing American novel; a true capital-R Romantic, f=
ull of an unshakable belief in the essential beauty and possibility of the =
world. A minor set piece in her great obituary for Jimmy Buffett [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/83ae8fa9-7ea6-44c5-8c1a-bf32d84aca86?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5q=
Z29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ] (which, by the way, c=
ompletely changed my perspective on the man from Margaritaville) seems to m=
e to exemplify this attitude:
That weekend I=E2=80=99d reached the stage of tax evasion where the feds qu=
it bothering with letters and simply help themselves to your savings accoun=
t without so much as a how do you do, and a day at the beach with a paperba=
ck seemed like the only reasonable response [...] By sunset I=E2=80=99d rea=
d the thing cover to cover, breaking between stories to go for a swim or mi=
x up a thermos of Diet Dark =E2=80=98n=E2=80=99 Stormy. Not only had Tales =
>From Margaritaville swept me away from my problems and into a world of jasm=
ine and plumeria, oysters and beer, pretty waitresses, limbo contests, and =
a drink called the Goombay Smash, I also was starting to get what made Jimm=
y Buffett tick.
Life might be an ongoing series of setbacks, bad beats, and humiliations, b=
ut it doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily preclude you from the small pleasures. An=
d it=E2=80=99s those small pleasures=E2=80=94the decisions to chat up the w=
aitress, to pull over at the weird roadside attraction, to ride your bike d=
own to the shores of Lake Michigan and spend the day with a few drinks and =
a book=E2=80=94that add up to form a life well-lived.
Throughout our conversation, Garvey occasionally pauses to make asides to t=
he effect of: I know things are often bad, I know America isn=E2=80=99t all=
 sunshine and roses. I=E2=80=99m not saying things were better in 1956, or =
whatever. It=E2=80=99s a familiar disclaimer, one I=E2=80=99ve issued many =
times myself. Anyone interested in the mythopoetic aspects of America has t=
o take pains to distance themselves from the poisonous nostalgia that chara=
cterizes so much of our political life. But lately I=E2=80=99ve had cause t=
o think that rather than make a preemptive apology for all the evil and cru=
elty in the world, the best thing one can do to counter it is put forward a=
 competing vision, like hers: an eerie and beautiful world of highways at n=
ight and lonesome train whistles and ghosts singing in the wires, of outlaw=
s, eccentrics, and strangers who are, for the most part, good-natured. By s=
ticking to this vision and refusing to take the world on the terms set by t=
he forces of greed and darkness, Garvey has crafted a life worth reading ab=
out and developed an inimitable voice that makes her=E2=80=94hell, I=E2=80=
=99ll say it=E2=80=94one of America=E2=80=99s great contemporary writers. =
=E2=80=9CYou have to make the choice,=E2=80=9D she tells me. =E2=80=9CNot t=
o be all, like, pull yourself up by your bootstraps, but to a large degree =
it=E2=80=99s a matter of temperament. Mystery and amusement and fascinating=
 stories can be found just about anywhere, so long as you are looking.=E2=
=80=9D

